      "markdown": "of current commonly acquired MRI scans (\"community MRI, cMRI\") and the degree of disability experienced by a patient.\nPURPOSE: This study examines the predictive ability of current MRI sequences relative to \"advanced MRI\" (aMRI) metrics designed to detect evidence of spinal cord injury secondary to degenerative myelopathy. We hypothesize that the utilization of higher fidelity aMRI scans will increase the effectiveness of machine learning models predicting DCM severity and may ultimately lead to a more efficient protocol for identifying patients in need of surgical intervention.\nSTUDY DESIGN/SETTING: Single institution analysis of imaging registry of patients with DCM. PATIENT SAMPLE: A total of 296 patients in the cMRI group and 228 patients in the aMRI group. OUTCOME MEASURES: Physiologic measures: accuracy of machine learning algorithms to detect severity of DCM assessed clinically based on the modified Japanese Orthopedic Association (mJOA) scale.\nMETHODS: Patients enrolled in the Canadian Spine Outcomes Research Network registry with DCM were screened and 296 cervical spine MRIs acquired in cMRI were compared with 228 aMRI acquisitions. aMRI acquisitions consisted of diffusion tensor imaging, magnetization transfer, $\\mathrm{T}_{2}$-weighted, and $\\mathrm{T}_{2} \\mathrm{~A}$-weighted images. The cMRI group consisted of only $\\mathrm{T}_{2}$-weighted MRI scans. Various machine learning models were applied to both MRI groups to assess accuracy of prediction of baseline disease severity assessed clinically using the mJOA scale for cervical myelopathy.\nRESULTS: Through the utilization of Random Forest Classifiers, disease severity was predicted with $41.8 \\%$ accuracy in cMRI scans and $73.3 \\%$ in the aMRI scans. Across different predictive model variations tested, the aMRI scans consistently produced higher prediction accuracies compared to the cMRI counterparts.\nCONCLUSIONS: aMRI metrics perform better in machine learning models at predicting disease severity of patients with DCM. Continued work is needed to refine these models and address DCM severity class imbalance concerns, ultimately improving model confidence for clinical implementation. (c) 2024 The Author(s). Published by Elsevier Inc. This is an open access article under the CC BY-NC-ND license (http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/)\n\nKeywords: Artificial intelligence; DCM; Degenerative cervical myelopathy; Machine learning; Magnetic resonance imaging; Spinal cord injury\n\n## Introduction\n\nDegenerative cervical myelopathy (DCM) occurs following chronic compression of the cervical spinal cord and is recognized as the most common form of atraumatic spinal cord injury globally [1]. The symptoms of DCM typically include gait imbalance, pain, loss of hand function, weakness and/or numbness [2].\n\nDCM is first diagnosed clinically and then confirmed with magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) of the cervical spine. Current surgical decision-making paradigms use MRI data to aid in surgical planning but not to identify the extent of spinal cord injury, as the clinical correlation of these findings remains unclear. Surgeons evaluate the severity of disease by obtaining a clinical history of symptoms and a physical examination of the affected individual. In patients with symptomatic progression or at least moderate impairment in disease severity, surgery is the only effective treatment for DCM. In appropriate patients, surgical decompression and potential fusion are thought to limit ongoing damage to the spinal cord in the form of demyelination, axonal damage or ischemia [3]. Although surgery carries important risks, including both short and long-term complications,hese complications are patient and treatment specific [4], and could include dysphagia, infection, and potential neurological and/or functional decline [5]. As a result, patient selection becomes a critical factor in the\noverall determination of outcomes for patients with DCM by balancing risks and benefits.\n\nDCM is often stratified using the modified Japanese Orthopaedic Association (mJOA) scale [6]. The mJOA aims to capture functional and neurological deficiency as a result of DCM through evaluating upper and lower extremity motor dysfunction, upper extremity sensory dysfunction, and sphincter dysfunction. A patient's mJOA score can range from 18 (no neurological deficits) to 0 (complete inability to move hands, complete loss of urinary sphincter control, and total loss of hand sensation) [7]. mJOA scores can be split into severity categories: mild (mJOA $\\geq 15$ ), moderate (mJOA score between 12 and 14), or severe (mJOA of $<12$ ) disease severity [8].\n\nThe work presented in this study addresses an opportunity to improve clinical care by attempting to improve the prediction of severityof disease at the time of MR imaging. In the age of automated analyses and alerts to specialized care teams, surgeons could be made aware of the extent of spinal cord injury sooner and with more confidence than through traditional referral and triage pathways that rely on reporting of clinical signs and symptoms. That being said, the MRI scan types used for severity prediction remain under question. Traditionally, T2w MRI imaging is conducted on individuals with DCM [9] yet evidence suggests that alternative imaging types such as Diffusion Tensor"
    },
    {
      "markdown": "Imaging (DTI) or Magnetization Transfer Scans (MT) may provide further insight into spinal cord demyelination and axon integrity [10,11], which are important markers of disease progression. Furthermore, it has been shown that compression severity may not be directly linked with DCM severity, warranting the use of advanced metrics of axon integrity and demylination to better predict disease severity $[12,13]$.\n\nIn this study, we aim to develop and test machine learning (ML) models tasked with predicting DCM disease severity through the use of MRI-derived quantitative metrics. We compared the accuracy of these machine learning models in predicting disease severity between routine community acquired MRI (cMRI) and an advanced MRI (aMRI) protocol that was developed to evaluate chronic spinal cord injury [14-16]. The aMRI dataset included advanced imaging biomarkers of disease severity which are actively being considered for diagnostic and prognostic abilities [15], whose effectiveness has yet to be determined. By applying the same ML training protocol to cMRI and aMRI data, a direct comparison can be made between the imaging protocols in predicting DCM severity. Through doing this, we aim to better understand if advanced MRI metrics can support the prediction of DCM baseline severity more than traditional cMRI metrics.\n\n## Material and methods\n\n## Study subjects\n\nThe University of Calgary Spine Program is a group of spine-fellowship trained orthopedic and neurological surgeons caring for a population of approximately 2 million persons in Southern Alberta. Since 2016, patients presenting to the clinics with a diagnosis of DCM have been enrolled into the Canadian Spine Outcomes Research Network registry, with approval from the institutional ethics review board (ethics certificate number REB-15-1332). Each patient provided written consent to participate and was followed through the study for 10 years or until the patient withdrew. Patients were offered enrollment into our registry under either the observational or surgical arm provided they do not meet any exclusion criteria. These criteria include previous cervical spinal surgery, concomitant neurological disease (such as multiple sclerosis or stroke), and a new MRI diagnosis of neoplasm or infection. We refer to this dataset as the \"community MRI (cMRI)\" dataset. A full breakdown of the various testing protocols for the community MRI dataset used in this study can be found in our research center's previously published work [17].\n\nA subset of the above listed patients from 2017-2023 were enrolled in a concurrent longitudinal study titled \"Personalized decision making after a diagnosis of cervical myelopathy: quantitative MRI within an artificial intelligence framework.\" This study has been approved by our\ninstitutional research ethics board (certificate number REB-18-1614), and each patient provided additional consent for the collection of an advanced MRI (aMRI) protocol that includes diffusion tensor imaging (DTI), magnetization transfer (MT), and $\\mathrm{T}_{2}{ }^{*}$-weighted image acquisitions in addition to an updated, higher fidelity, $\\mathrm{T}_{2}$-weighted scan. The rationale for the aMRI protocol can be found in the spine generic acquisition protocol paper [16]. A summary of the varying scans and metrics in the aMRI dataset is provided in Table 1.\n\n## Image acquisition\n\nAll aMRI data was acquired on a 3T GE scanner. Subjects were carefully positioned to limit head movement and requested to not move. cMRI scanner models differed as they came from multiple centres across Alberta.\n\nA $\\mathrm{T}_{2}$-weighted acquisition was acquired as follows: FIESTA-C sequence ( $\\mathrm{T}_{2}$-weighted); $512 \\times 512$, NEX 1.0 , FOV 200 mm , slice thickness 0.4 mm ; resulting in a voxel size of $0.4 \\times 0.4 \\times 0.4 \\mathrm{~mm}^{3}$, collected in the coronal plane. The total scan time was approximately 5 minutes per patient. aMRI records also contain sequences suggested in the spine-generic protocol, namely: DTI, MT, and $\\mathrm{T}_{2}{ }^{*}$ weighted image acquisitions, each with 13 axial slices across the C 1 to C 7 vertebrae, using a variable gap to alternate between bone and intervertebral discs. DTI used spinecho single shot echo planar imaging (ssEPI) with 3 acquisitions averaged offline, $\\mathrm{b}=800 \\mathrm{~s} / \\mathrm{mm}^{2}$ in 25 directions, 5 images with $\\mathrm{b}=0 \\mathrm{~s} / \\mathrm{mm}^{2}$, and resolution of $1 \\times 1 \\times 5 \\mathrm{~mm}^{3}$ ( 7 minutes total). MT used 2D spoiled gradient echo with/ without MT prepulse (offset $=1.2 \\mathrm{kHz}$ ), with $1 \\times 1 \\times 5 \\mathrm{~mm}^{3}$ voxels, for 8 minutes total. $\\mathrm{T}_{2}{ }^{*}$-weighted acquisitions used a 2D Multi-Echo Recombined Gradient Echo (MERGE) with 3 echoes at 5,10 , and 15 ms , each with a resolution $0.6 \\times 0.6 \\times 4 \\mathrm{~mm}^{3}$ without interpolation. Total imaging time for all acquisitions together came to approximately 30 minutes after accounting for patient positioning, slice prescription, and high-order shimming.\n\n## Clinical assessment\n\nThe validated modified Japanese Orthopedic Association (mJOA) score was recorded for each patient at the time of diagnosis by the neurosurgeon who enrolled the patient. mJOA severity class was used as the primary target variable in all machine learning models. cMRI and aMRI dataset features were tested as independent variables for model predictions.\n\n## Computational tools\n\nThe versions of the tools used for these methods were as follows: scikit-learn v.0.23.2 [18], pandas v.1.1.3 [19], numpy v.1.19.2 [20], Spinal Cord Toolbox v.4.3 [21], matplotlib v.3.3.2 [22], and FSLeyes v.0.34.2 [23]."
    },
