      "markdown": "Table 1\nOverview of MRI scan types and derived features from these scans\n\n| Metrics of cord compression | Features | Description |\n| :--: | :--: | :--: |\n| $\\mathrm{T}_{2}$-weighted scan | Spinal cord cross-sectional area, vertebral level segmentation | Standard protocol MRI scan sequence [16]. It was used for both community and advanced MRI datasets presented and provides anatomical information. |\n| Metrics of axonal Integrity |  |  |\n| Diffusion tensor imaging | Fractional anisotropy (FA) in spinal cord white matter as a measure of axonal integrity | Captures evidence of directional diffusion of water in tissues [17]. They have shown promising results in the detection of DCM [10]. Fractional anisotropy has been found to be particularly sensitive [10]. |\n| Metrics of demyelination |  |  |\n| $\\mathrm{T}_{2}{ }^{*}$-weighted scan** | Spinal cord white matter (WM) area and spinal cord grey matter (GM) area including WM/GM signal ratio | $\\mathrm{T}_{2} * \\mathrm{w}$ is a gradient signal echo image. $\\mathrm{T}_{2} * \\mathrm{w}$ images have been found to be useful in small lesion detection and the quantification of early degenerative disease [18]. |\n| Magnetization transfer (MT) scan*** | Magnetization transfer ratio (MTR) in white matter | MT scans are useful for contrast augmentation [19]. MT scans have been found to detect myelin degradation in patients with DCM [11]. |\n\n** Used only in advanced MRI acquisition protocol.\n\n## MRI scan preprocessing\n\nAll raw DICOM data in the cMRI and aMRI datasets was extracted and anonymized using the \"dcm2bids\" package [24], converting them into a BIDS-compliant format [25]. Each patient record was manually inspected to confirm data integrity. Records were excluded if they contained motion artefacts, were mislabeled (eg, the MRI were of the thoracic spine, rather than the cervical spine as labelled), and/or had an insufficient slice count (resulting in the inability for segmentation algorithms to make accurate estimates of spinal cord metrics).\n\n## Spinal cord MRI analysis\n\nSpinal Cord Toolbox (SCT), an all-in-one MRI processing package specialized in spinal cord MRI scans [21], was used for image segmentation for both cMRI and aMRI datasets. The segmentation of the spinal cord was performed for both the cMRI and aMRI datasets using the SCT's \"sct_deepseg_sc\" command [26] or the $\\mathrm{T}_{2}$-weighted, $\\mathrm{T}_{2}{ }^{*}$ weighted, and MT scans. SCT's \"propseg\" command [27] as used for the DTI scan. An example of these segmentations is shown in Fig. 1.\n![img-0.jpeg](img-0.jpeg)\n\nFig. 1. MRI scan visualization and segmentation using the Spinal Cord Toolbox. Images were captured at the C3 level of a control patient. Top thumbnails show the image without segmentation, and bottom images include segmentation. (Left to Right) $\\mathrm{T}_{2}{ }^{*}$-weighted grey matter (red) and white matter (blue) scan, $\\mathrm{T}_{2}$-weighted, magnetization transfer scan, and fractional anisotropy. MT=Magnetization Transfer; DTI=Diffusion Tensor Imaging."
    },
    {
      "markdown": "MRI-derived morphometrics were then extracted from the $\\mathrm{T}_{2}$-weighted (spinal cord cross-sectional area) and $\\mathrm{T}_{2}{ }^{*}$ weighted (spinal cord grey matter cross-sectional area) segmentations using SCT's \"sct_process_segmentation\" function, creating the features used by our machine learning models. These features included the cross-sectional area, angle between centerline and axial slice in the anterior-posterior (AP) axis and right-left (RL) axis, distance between the major and minor axis of the cord (diameter) in the AP and RL axis, ratio of the focal distance over the major axis length (eccentricity), angle between AP axis of the spinal cord and AP axis of the image (orientation), spinal cord solidity, and spinal cord length [21]. This resulted in 9 features per vertebrae in the $\\mathrm{T}_{2}$-weighted acquisition and 7 features per vertebrae in the $\\mathrm{T}_{2}{ }^{*}$-weighted acquisition (as $\\mathrm{T}_{2}{ }^{*}$-weighted does not contain Angle AP and Angle RL values). DTI and MT scans were analyzed using SCT's \"sct_extract_metric\" script to generate the \"maximum a posteriori\" (MAP) fractional anisotropy value in white matter and magnetization transfer ratio in white matter, respectively [21].\n\nAdditionally, all MRI-derived metrics, we calculated the overall mean, standard deviation, maximum value, minimum value, and the difference between maximum and minimum values ( $\\Delta$ ) for all metrics between the C 2 and T 1 vertebral levels. Age and sex of the patient were included as features in both datasets. This resulted in 53 features overall for the cMRI dataset and 149 features overall for the aMRI dataset (Appendix A for full list).\n\n## Management of missing clinical and excluded metrics\n\nPatients missing a recorded mJOA value or more than 20 percent of their imaging metrics were excluded. Sparsely missing features were imputed using scikitlearn's \"SimpleImputer.\" A specific breakdown of excluded patients can be found in Fig. 2. Metrics from the C 1 level in the $\\mathrm{T}_{2}$-weighted and MT scan, the C 1 -C3 and C7 level of the $\\mathrm{T}_{2}{ }^{*}$-weighted scan, and the $\\mathrm{C} 1, \\mathrm{C} 6$, and C 7 level of the DTI scan were excluded as the SCT automated analysis provided inconsistent and poor registration likely as a result of being near the edge of the scan region introducing an unreasonable amount of noise to the ML model.\n\n## Prediction of baseline disease severity and model performance\n\nBoth cMRI and aMRI datasets were split into a training set of 65 percent of the data and a testing set of 35 percent. All features were scaled to a unit norm using SciKit-Learn's \"StandardScaler\" class. The mJOA score was also binned into 3 primary categories: mild severity (mJOA $\\geq 15$ ), moderate severity ( $\\mathrm{mJOA}=12-14$ ) and severe severity (mJOA $<$ 12) [8]. Three target metrics, as opposed to individual mJOA score predictions, allows the ML model to overcome interrater variablity that is often seen with mJOA evaluation while using a categorical system that has been found to support the assessment of DCM disease severity [8].\n![img-1.jpeg](img-1.jpeg)\n\nFig. 2. Breakdown of patient enrolment pathway and patient disease severity. Following excluded patients and scans, 296 cMRI patients were included. Of these patients, a subset of 228 patients were enrolled into the aMRI group. In the cMRI group, there were an equal number of mild and moderately severe patients ( $\\mathrm{n}=114$ and $\\mathrm{n}=115$, respectively) with a decrease in the amount of severe mJOA patients ( $\\mathrm{n}=67$ ). In the aMRI group, there was an abundance of mild severity patients ( $\\mathrm{n}=161$ ) as compared to moderate ( $\\mathrm{n}=31$ ) and severe groups ( $\\mathrm{n}=22$ ). mJOA=modified Japanese Orthopaedic Association."
    },
    {
      "markdown": "Feature preprocessing methodologies were tested with and without Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE) and with and without dimensionality reduction (using Principal Component Analysis (PCA) or Linear Discriminant Analysis (LDA) when dimensionality reduction was employed), with the resulting features being used to train and test Random Forest Classifier models [18]. A pipeline of each permutation was run in the order they are listed, with each being fed into a Random Forest Classifier, including hyperparameter tuning. Random Forest Classifiers were selected over Logistic Regression, Gradient Boosting Classifier, and Support Vector Classification models based on their performance in preliminary tests.\n\nAccuracy, precision, and recall including a stratifeid 5fold cross validation were calculated for each model generated using the model's predicted mJOA severity class and the patient's true mJOA severity class [18]. Both cMRI and aMRI datasets underwent the same analysis pipeline.\n\n## Results\n\n## Patient enrolment\n\nA total of 394 patients were enrolled in the study from 2016 to 2021. Of the enrolled patients, 380 had a baseline mJOA recorded. Of these, 296 cMRI records met the criteria for inclusion in this study. A total of 228 patients were simultaneously enrolled in the collection of advanced, dis-ease-specific metrics. 214 of these patients had a baseline mJOA and were included in our aMRI dataset. A visualization of the enrolled patients can be seen in Fig. 2.\n\n## Predicting baseline severity in cMRI scan metrics\n\nThe cMRI dataset consisted of 53 derived features from each of the 296 MRI records. The testing accuracy of the model training on data without RFE or LDA/PCA was 41.8 $\\%$, which decreased to $41.1 \\%$ with RFE, and continued on a downward trend with the addition of LDA and PCA (Table 2). In the cMRI group, testing and training accuracies remained relatively the same except for the RFC + LDA model which differed by $30.6 \\%$ accuracy. The Random Forest Classifier model alone performed the best with an accuracy of $41.8 \\%$. The RFC + RFE + LDA model performed the worst with an accuracy of $27.6 \\%$ (Fig. 5).\n\nPrecision and recall scores followed the same trend and performed within $10 \\%$ of their model's respective accuracy. RFE identified 32 of the 53 features as the optimum number of features for the model's performance (Appendix B). The cMRI prediction model performs similarly in predicting mild and moderate disease severities ( $46.0 \\%$ correct and $47.9 \\%$ correct, respectively) but misinterprets all severe mJOA patients as milder (Fig. 3).\n\n## Predicting baseline severity in aMRI scan metrics\n\nThe advanced MRI metrics consisted of 149 features derived from the $\\mathrm{T}_{2}$-weighted, $\\mathrm{T}_{2}{ }^{*}$-weighted, DTI and MT scans. The initial testing accuracy of the model was $73.3 \\%$ which decreased slightly with preprocessing permutations yet remained within $\\sim 6 \\%$ of the initial accuracy (Table 3). RFC + RFE + LDA and RFC + LDA were the two exceptions, dropping down to $50.7 \\%$ and $36.0 \\%$ accuracy, respectively. The Random Forest Classifier model alone performed the best with an accuracy of $73.3 \\%$ but may have overfit with a training accuracy of $1.0 \\%$. The RFC + LDA model performed the worst with an accuracy of $36.0 \\%$. Precision and recall scores followed the same trend and performed within $15 \\%$ of their model's respective accuracy. RFE identified 74 of the 149 features as the optimum number of features for the model's performance (Appendix C). The confusion matrix indicates that the model predicted mild disease severity ( $70 \\%$ correct) most consistently followed by severe DCM ( $38 \\%$ correct) and moderate DCM (36\\%) (Fig. 3).\n\n## Discussion\n\nThis work compares the utility of community acquired diagnostic MRI scans with advanced MRI acquisitions to predict the severity of DCM at the time of diagnosis. The aMRI acquisition protocol was initially designed to capture evidence of spinal cord injury such as demyelination or axonal damage whereas community MRI acquisitions captured evidence of cord compression. The significance of this work lies with the novel implementation of machine learning models with aMRI acquisitions to better help physicians prioritize patients during triage and during diagnosis. This is important as MRI acquisition protocols for individuals with CSM have remained relatively unchanged\n\nTable 2\nSummarized cross-validated accuracy, precision score, and recall score for tested model variations in the cMRI group\n\n| Model variations | Cross-validated accuracy (testing set) | Cross-validated accuracy (training set) | Specificity | Sensitivity |\n| :-- | :-- | :-- | :-- | :-- |\n| RFC only | 0.418 | 0.370 | 0.343 | 0.343 |\n| RFC+RFE | 0.411 | 0.499 | 0.381 | 0.381 |\n| RFC+RFE+PCA | 0.365 | 0.444 | 0.328 | 0.328 |\n| RFC+RFE+LDA | 0.276 | 0.481 | 0.351 | 0.351 |\n| RFC+PCA | 0.395 | 0.481 | 0.291 | 0.291 |\n| RFC+LDA | 0.298 | 0.604 | 0.388 | 0.388 |\n\n[^0]\n[^0]:    RFC=Random Forest Classifier; RFE=Recurssive Feature Elimination; PCA=Principal Component Analysis; LDA=Linear Discriminant Analysis."
