      "markdown": "![img-2.jpeg](img-2.jpeg)\n\nFig. 3. Confusion Matrix for cMRI and aMRI dataset model predictions across mJOA categories for baseline disease severity. The cMRI prediction model performed equally in predicting mild and moderate baseline disease severity with $46 \\%$ correct and $52 \\%$ correct, respectively. The cMRI prediction model was not able to predict any of the severe testing patients correctly. That being said, the model favors making moderate predictions (n=66) slightly more than mild predictions ( $\\mathrm{n}=64$ ). It favors both mild and moderate predictions more than severe predictions ( $\\mathrm{n}=4$ ). The aMRI model predicts $70 \\%$ of the mild patients correctly, $36 \\%$ of the moderate patients correctly, and $38 \\%$ of the severe patients correctly.\nsince the 1980s while the available analysis tools and scans have improved [9]. Furthermore, through analyzing which specific metrics had the most profound impact on disease severity prediction, we are better able to determine which scans should be prioritized by physicians. Ultimately, this work aimed to understand if aMRI metrics can better support DCM severity prediction than cMRI metrics alone.\n\nWe demonstrated that overall aMRI acquisitions outperform cMRI in baseline disease severity prediction (Fig. 5). That being said, the aMRI and cMRI datasets had substantial class imbalances due to the nature of the patient population and the likelihood of milder patients enrolling in research studies. These class imbalances must be taken into consideration when comparing and evaluating model evaluation metrics. In addition, we demonstrated that cMRI acquisitions alone fail to accurately predict disease severity when utilizing simple machine learning models. The cMRI dataset did not surpass $42 \\%$ accuracy in any of the testing models despite the inclusion of RFE and PCA/LDA. Furthermore, the cMRI prediction model appeared to act naively in predicting severe disease severity, failing to accurately identify any patients with severe DCM. We suspect that this is due to imbalance in the cMRI dataset with a\nmajority ( $77 \\%$ ) of patients being mild and moderate severity, biasing predictions towards the more common mild and moderate DCM classes. It may also indicate that the cMRIderived metrics are insufficient for simple machine learning models to function effectively or that these simple models simply cannot work effectively with cMRI-derived metrics. The cMRI set is limited to only metrics capturing metrics of spinal cord compression. With previous studies showing that focal compression of the spinal cord may not correlate with disease severity, it is likely that the cMRI model simply did not have enough information to accurately capture the severity of DCM present [13].\n\nIn the aMRI dataset, the model's performance begins to plateau past 25 features and fully levels out with minor fluctuation beyond 55 features (Fig. 4). This indicates that there are many possible combinations of features that can be used to predict disease severity, though many of these combinations are also redundant. Of the 74 features that were ranked as optimal by RFE, $27 \\mathrm{~T}_{2}$-weighted metrics were selected, $41 \\mathrm{~T}_{2}{ }^{*}$-weighted metrics were selected, 4 DT scan metrics were selected, and 2 MT scan metrics were selected. With more than half stemming from aMRIderived features, it is apparent that the accuracy benefits\n\nTable 3\nSummarized cross-validated accuracy, precision score, and recall score for tested model variations in the aMRI group\n\n| Model variations | Cross-validated accuracy (testing set) | Cross-validated accuracy (training set) | Precision score | Recall score |\n| :-- | :-- | :-- | :-- | :-- |\n| RFC only | 0.733 | 1.0 | 0.555 | 0.327 |\n| RFC+RFE | 0.640 | 0.842 | 0.669 | 0.455 |\n| RFC+RFE+PCA | 0.613 | 0.778 | 0.673 | 0.478 |\n| RFC+RFE+LDA | 0.507 | 0.683 | 0.682 | 0.359 |\n| RFC+PCA | 0.680 | 0.993 | 0.629 |